                                                                                <item><title><![CDATA[7 TV Trends That Were Doomed to Fail]]></title><link>https://www.howtogeek.com/tv-trends-that-were-doomed/</link><dc:creator><![CDATA[Rich Hein]]></dc:creator><enclosure url="https://static0.howtogeekimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/rear-projection-tv-with-the-word-failed-in-bold-red-text-surrounded-by-thumbs-down-icons.png" length="992" type="image/jpeg"/><category><![CDATA[Audio/Video]]></category><category><![CDATA[Television]]></category><category><![CDATA[Streaming]]></category><description><![CDATA[
                                            From 3D TVs to curved screens, some ‘next big things’ in home theater never lived up to the hype. Here’s why these TV trends failed.
                                        ]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[
                                                                                                                                    <p>I‘ve always been a fan of <a href="https://www.howtogeek.com/home-theater-sound-basics-a-beginners-guide-to-better-movie-audio/" target="_blank">home theater</a> and TV technology. Over the decades, I’ve tried many of the “next big things” the industry has offered: projectors, rear-projection TVs, a 43” tube TV that felt huge at the time, and for a short while a curved TV. Looking back, it’s been a fun ride, but many so-called “game changers” never lived up to the hype.</p>                    ]]></content:encoded><pubDate>Fri, 10 Oct 2025 16:30:16 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.howtogeek.com/tv-trends-that-were-doomed/</guid></item>                                                                <item><title><![CDATA[Windows Copilot Is Getting More Productivity Upgrades]]></title><link>https://www.howtogeek.com/windows-copilot-is-getting-more-productivity-upgrades/</link><dc:creator><![CDATA[Jorge A. Aguilar]]></dc:creator><enclosure url="https://static0.howtogeekimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/bing-copilot-logo.jpg" length="83" type="image/jpeg"/><category><![CDATA[Windows]]></category><category><![CDATA[copilot]]></category><description><![CDATA[
                                            You shouldn't have to copy and paste as much anymore.
                                        ]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[
                                                                                                                                    <p>Microsoft has started rolling out a new update for the Copilot app on Windows to Windows Insiders. The biggest additions are the introduction of Connectors for personal services and the ability to create and export documents directly from your Copilot session.</p>                    ]]></content:encoded><pubDate>Fri, 10 Oct 2025 16:13:25 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.howtogeek.com/windows-copilot-is-getting-more-productivity-upgrades/</guid></item>                                                                <item><title><![CDATA[Anker’s New Portable Projector Has a Unique Audio Upgrade]]></title><link>https://www.howtogeek.com/ankers-new-portable-projector-has-a-unique-audio-upgrade/</link><dc:creator><![CDATA[Cory Gunther]]></dc:creator><enclosure url="https://static0.howtogeekimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/nebula-p1-projector.jpg" length="1369" type="image/jpeg"/><category><![CDATA[Audio/Video]]></category><category><![CDATA[Projector]]></category><category><![CDATA[Anker]]></category><category><![CDATA[Nebula]]></category><description><![CDATA[
                                            The Anker Nebula P1 has detachable speakers, along with Google TV and other impressive features.
                                        ]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[
                                                                                                                                    <p>Portable projectors are a great way to enjoy a backyard movie night on a fall evening, and they're a good alternative to big-screen TVs. Anker's sub-brand Nebula just debuted the P1, the world's first portable projector with detachable speakers.</p>                    ]]></content:encoded><pubDate>Fri, 10 Oct 2025 16:02:01 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.howtogeek.com/ankers-new-portable-projector-has-a-unique-audio-upgrade/</guid></item>                                                                <item><title><![CDATA[Visual Studio Code's Latest Update Adds More OS Integrations]]></title><link>https://www.howtogeek.com/visual-studio-codes-latest-update-adds-more-os-integrations/</link><dc:creator><![CDATA[Jorge A. Aguilar]]></dc:creator><enclosure url="https://static0.howtogeekimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/visual-studio-code.jpg" length="199" type="image/jpeg"/><category><![CDATA[Programming]]></category><category><![CDATA[Programming]]></category><description><![CDATA[
                                            Fitting in with the rest of your apps.
                                        ]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[
                                                                                                                                    <p>Visual Studio Code's September 2025 release (version 1.105) has officially dropped, but a little late since it is October already. This update focuses on better operating system integration, developer productivity, and adding to the experience with remote coding tools.</p>                    ]]></content:encoded><pubDate>Fri, 10 Oct 2025 15:45:32 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.howtogeek.com/visual-studio-codes-latest-update-adds-more-os-integrations/</guid></item>                                                                <item><title><![CDATA[What Does the ChromeOS and Android Merger Mean for You?]]></title><link>https://www.howtogeek.com/what-does-the-chromeos-and-android-merger-mean-for-you/</link><dc:creator><![CDATA[Sydney Butler]]></dc:creator><enclosure url="https://static0.howtogeekimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/wm/2025/08/oneplus-13r-sitting-on-an-hp-chromebook-plus.jpg" length="422" type="image/jpeg"/><category><![CDATA[Chromebook & Chrome OS]]></category><category><![CDATA[Google]]></category><category><![CDATA[Chromebook]]></category><category><![CDATA[Linux]]></category><category><![CDATA[Android Phones & Tablets]]></category><description><![CDATA[
                                            So this is what it's like when world's collide.
                                        ]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[
                                                                                                                                    <p>Google has announced that <a href="https://www.howtogeek.com/android-and-chromebooks-will-eventually-merge/" target="_self">ChromeOS and Android will become one unified operating system</a> at some point in the future. That's no small goal, and it's going to have a knock-on effect for both hardware and software. </p>                    ]]></content:encoded><pubDate>Fri, 10 Oct 2025 15:30:16 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.howtogeek.com/what-does-the-chromeos-and-android-merger-mean-for-you/</guid></item>                                                                <item><title><![CDATA[The Infinix HOT 60 Pro+ Is Officially the World's Thinnest 3D Curved Display Smartphone]]></title><link>https://www.howtogeek.com/infinix-hot-50-pro-plus-curved-smartphone/</link><dc:creator><![CDATA[Sponsored]]></dc:creator><enclosure url="https://static0.howtogeekimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/_dsc5160-25-08-09.jpg" length="432" type="image/jpeg"/><category><![CDATA[Promoted]]></category><description><![CDATA[
                                            This post is sponsored by Infinix.
                                        ]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[
                                                                                                                                    <p>Slimness has become an industry trend. Smartphone makers are competing to deliver devices that feel lighter and sleeker, and even Apple has entered the race with the iPhone 17 Air.</p>                    ]]></content:encoded><pubDate>Fri, 10 Oct 2025 15:20:22 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.howtogeek.com/infinix-hot-50-pro-plus-curved-smartphone/</guid></item>                                                                <item><title><![CDATA[How to See All Devices on Your Network With nmap on Linux]]></title><link>https://www.howtogeek.com/423709/how-to-see-all-devices-on-your-network-with-nmap-on-linux/</link><dc:creator><![CDATA[Dave McKay]]></dc:creator><enclosure url="https://static0.howtogeekimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/52848912564_6cae6ce5f4_o.jpg" length="258" type="image/jpeg"/><category><![CDATA[Linux]]></category><category><![CDATA[Linux & macOS Terminal]]></category><category><![CDATA[Linux]]></category><category><![CDATA[Cloud & Internet]]></category><category><![CDATA[Wi-Fi Routers]]></category><description><![CDATA[
                                            It isn't as intuitive as a user interface, but it is more powerful. 
                                        ]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[
                                                                                                                                    <p>Think you know what's connected to your home network? You might be surprised. Learn how to check using <code>nmap</code> on Linux, which will let you explore all the devices connected to your network.</p>                    ]]></content:encoded><pubDate>Fri, 10 Oct 2025 14:30:15 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.howtogeek.com/423709/how-to-see-all-devices-on-your-network-with-nmap-on-linux/</guid></item>                                                                <item><title><![CDATA[Why Some Websites Block VPNs (and How They Catch You)]]></title><link>https://www.howtogeek.com/why-some-websites-block-vpns/</link><dc:creator><![CDATA[Shan Abdul]]></dc:creator><enclosure url="https://static0.howtogeekimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/52638820954_b8557161ae_o.jpg" length="302513" type="image/jpeg"/><category><![CDATA[Web]]></category><category><![CDATA[VPN]]></category><category><![CDATA[Privacy]]></category><category><![CDATA[Cybersecurity]]></category><description><![CDATA[
                                            VPNs meet website roadblocks!
                                        ]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[
                                                                                                                                    <p>Using a <span class="display-card-hyperlink-article" data-id="209487"><a href="/738071/best-vpn-services/" target="_blank">VPN</a></span> protects your privacy and helps you bypass regional restrictions—but not all services allow it. If you’ve ever faced issues accessing a platform while connected to a VPN, the platform is probably blocking VPN traffic. So why do some websites block a VPN, and how exactly do they detect it?</p>                    ]]></content:encoded><pubDate>Fri, 10 Oct 2025 14:15:15 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.howtogeek.com/why-some-websites-block-vpns/</guid></item>                                                                <item><title><![CDATA[Why Audiophiles Hate Soundbars (and Why They’re Wrong)]]></title><link>https://www.howtogeek.com/why-audiophiles-hate-soundbars-and-why-theyre-wrong/</link><dc:creator><![CDATA[Sydney Butler]]></dc:creator><enclosure url="https://static0.howtogeekimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/looking-at-the-bose-smart-ultra-soundbar-from-the-left.jpg" length="397" type="image/jpeg"/><category><![CDATA[Audio/Video]]></category><category><![CDATA[Speakers]]></category><category><![CDATA[Audio]]></category><category><![CDATA[TVs]]></category><category><![CDATA[Soundbar]]></category><description><![CDATA[
                                            Don't knock it till you try it.
                                        ]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[
                                                                                                                                    <p>An "audiophile" is someone who loves the experience of high-fidelity sound reproduction and appreciates a good soundstage and audio imaging. In fact, achieving higher levels of fidelity and more accurate sound reproduction is a goal that many audiophiles chase relentlessly—often at great cost.</p>                    ]]></content:encoded><pubDate>Fri, 10 Oct 2025 14:00:15 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.howtogeek.com/why-audiophiles-hate-soundbars-and-why-theyre-wrong/</guid></item>                                                                <item><title><![CDATA[3 Cool Linux Apps Worth Trying This Weekend (October 10 - 12)]]></title><link>https://www.howtogeek.com/linux-apps-to-try-this-weekend-october-10/</link><dc:creator><![CDATA[Jordan Gloor]]></dc:creator><enclosure url="https://static0.howtogeekimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/a-laptop-seen-from-the-front-running-linux-lite-with-two-other-distros-in-the-background.png" length="997" type="image/jpeg"/><category><![CDATA[Linux]]></category><category><![CDATA[Apps & Web Apps]]></category><category><![CDATA[Weekend]]></category><category><![CDATA[Linux & macOS Terminal]]></category><category><![CDATA[Open Source]]></category><description><![CDATA[
                                            Ready to browse the web from your Linux computer like it's 2008?
                                        ]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[
                                                                                                                                    <p>The weekend is the perfect time to put your Linux PC to the test and see what you can actually do with it. These are some native Linux applications I think are worth trying out if you haven't already installed them.</p>                    ]]></content:encoded><pubDate>Fri, 10 Oct 2025 13:00:16 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.howtogeek.com/linux-apps-to-try-this-weekend-october-10/</guid></item></channel>
